  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that modern supply‑chain attacks exploit a single careless action that gains access to a developer’s extensive credential store, so defenses must limit the blast radius of any “weird click.” It proposes a six‑step blueprint—isolating work in DevContainers, restricting mounts, scoping secrets, planting canarytokens, delaying updates with tools like pnpm’s minimumReleaseAge, and rapid incident response—to keep credentials “boring” and detect misuse early. The piece is a pragmatic, security‑focused tutorial aimed at software engineers, DevOps teams, and security practitioners, using the metaphor of a “credential cruise ship” and recurring imagery of canaries and boxes to frame its recommendations.",
